snippet.textDisplay: Do that many people just upgrade their CPU? I have no idea how many PCs I've built over the last 20 years and I don't remember ever just upgrading the CPU. I've always upgraded at least motherboard and CPU... And usually the memory too... Then I usually used my old components to build another system that I either sold or gave to someone else. Since I usually build a system every year, my year old computer was more than enough for those who received them. I find selling a complete system is easier than trying to sell just a single component like a CPU

snippet.textDisplay:
Ya know what amd should have done? Let the old boards have the updated bios. Then when instabilities, critical system failure, and bricks started happening because everyone wants to be total cheap-asses by trying to milk out every last dollar out of a 3 year old platform. Then when the same people who are upset about them making a logical decision to not push old architecture past its optimal performance ceiling get upset about dead PC's they can say "i told you so" 

Can't we appreciate that they have given us a really awesome 3 years of cost to profromce options? I for one have a b450 with a 2700x and love it. I did that this last black Friday. I'm not in the least bit disappointed that I can't just buy a new chip and be done. When I upgrade i want the best possible architecture for that chip. To be fair, amd is a business, they need to make money, they need to innovate, they need to change and grow, and using the same boards over and over won't do make them money. And it won't be a benefit to slap a 4th or 5th gen chip in a 5 year old MOBO and then get upset when you only get a 10%increase in profomace because its not ment to handle that chip form the future. It would be like taking a note 10 back 10 years and wondering why the old phone chargers can't charge it like the super fast chargers can. We all need to except that we might have been just a wee bit spoiled by amd and are now just kind of looking for hand outs, if this outrage ( more like temper tantrum) is anything to go by.
